    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-10T21:17:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-08T23:30:00-05:00" n="148"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d148">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/953: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Venezuelan Minister for Foreign Affairs</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Parra-Perez</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caracas</hi>
                        </placeName> [<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1941-12-10T21:47:00-04:30"
                            notBefore="1941-12-09T00:00:00-04:30">undated</date>].<lb/>[Received
                        December 10, 1941—9:47 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>With the position of Venezuela, which is one of complete solidarity with the
                    United States in the present serious moments, defined as it has been by the
                    President of the Republic, allow me, Excellency, to call to mind our friendly
                    and cordial collaboration in Buenos Aires and the identity of our Pan American
                    sentiments in order to renew to you the assurance that my country, sincerely
                    united in ideals of democracy and liberty to the American people, condemns the
                    aggression of which it has been the object by Japan and will cooperate in the
                    defense of the continent and of the principles common to all our countries.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">C. Parra-Perez</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
